==Military service==
[[File:Ephesus 06 28 09 0419.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Helles Memorial]] to the missing dead, where Capt Arthur Dingle is commemorated.]]
Since Dingle was a school master, he was exempt from military service, but having been a member of the Oxford University [[Officers Training Corps]] (OTC), and having set up the OTC at Durham School, he sought permission to enlist from the headmaster, [[Richard Budworth|Canon Budworth]].{{sfn|Cooper|2012}} He was commissioned on 29 August 1914 temporary [[second lieutenant]] into the 6th Battalion, [[East Yorkshire Regiment]].<ref name="ox.ac.uk"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28881|date=28 August 1914|startpage=6797|accessdate=21 July 1915}}</ref> He was promoted to temporary [[lieutenant]] on 8 December.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29031|supp=yes|date=5 January 1915|startpage=247|accessdate=21 July 2015}}</ref> 

Dingle's regiment was sent to [[Gallipoli Campaign|Gallipoli]] and took part in the [[Suvla Bay Landing|Suvla Bay landing]]s on 6 August 1915. His battalion soon took the small hill at Lala Baba, with the loss of many lives. Three days later, with Dingle made temporary captain,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29306|supp=yes|date=21 September 1915|startpage=9410|accessdate=21 July 2015}}</ref> his battalion captured Scimitar Hill, once again with great loss of life, but then made a tactical withdrawal. On 21 August, with Dingle as acting commanding officer of the 150 men of B Company,{{sfn|Cooper|2012}} the battalion was involved in the [[Battle of Scimitar Hill]], a major assault to recapture the hill, which ended in disaster.{{sfn|McCrery|2014|p=28}} Dingle was shot through the temple and killed at dawn on 22 August 1915, while defending a captured trench "against overwhelming odds".{{sfn|Massue|2000|p=100}}{{sfn|Sewell|1919|p=44}} It was not possible to recover his body.{{sfn|Hagger|2014}} Of his England team-mates who played Scotland in the final Calcutta Cup match in 1914 before the start of the war, three had already died:  [[Bungy Watson]], [[Francis Oakley]] and Poulton.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newspapers.library.wales/view/4092584/4092590/98/ | title=Another Rugby Cap Gone – South Wales Weekly Post | publisher=William Llewellyn Williams | date=2 October 1915 | accessdate=24 July 2015}}</ref>

''The Ballad of Suvla Bay'' by John Still, has these lines about Dingle:{{sfn|Sewell|1919|p=44}}
<blockquote>
{{ubl|Broad and simple and great of heart,
|Strenuous of soul in a stalwart frame,
|Whatever the work he took his part,
|With energy strung from the very start
|To learn the rules and play the game.
}}<br/>
{{ubl|He'd played for an English side before, 
|And all unspoiled by the crowd's applause,
|He took for his side their greeting roars.
|And so, in the greater game of war,
|He gave his life for his country's cause.
}}
</blockquote>

He is commemorated on panels 51 to 54 of the [[Helles Memorial]] to the missing.{{sfn|McCrery|2014|p=28}} Other rugby internationals commemorated on the monument include the two Scotsmen [[William Campbell Church]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/697125/CHURCH,%20WILLIAM%20CAMPBELL|title=CWGC – Casualty Details William Campbell Church|author=Reading Room Manchester|work=cwgc.org}}</ref> and [[Eric Templeton Young]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/1564448/YOUNG,%20ERIC%20TEMPLETON|title=CWGC – Casualty Details Eric Templeton Young|author=Reading Room Manchester|work=cwgc.org}}</ref> and the Englishman [[William Nanson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/689171/NANSON,%20WILLIAM|title=CWGC – Casualty Details William Nanson|author=Reading Room Manchester|work=cwgc.org}}</ref> There are also memorials to him at Durham School, St Margaret's Church in Durham, Keble College, Richmond, Rosslyn Park, Hartlepool Rovers and Oxford rugby club.{{sfn|Hagger|2014}} There is also a tournament played amongst some of the first schools to adopt rugby, the [[Veterrimi IV]], the winning team being awarded the AJ Dingle Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamschool.co.uk/newsarticle.asp?newsid=1765|title=A J Dingle Cup returns to Durham School|work=durhamschool.co.uk}}</ref>

